WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
FOREWORD VIKTOR FRANKL'S Man's Search for Meaning is one of

2
00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:06.960
the great books of our time. Typically, if a book

3
00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:10.440
has one passage, one idea with the power to change

4
00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:13.920
a person's life, that alone justiɹes reading it, rereading it,

5
00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:16.704
and ɹnding room for it on one's shelves.

6
00:00:16.704 --> 00:00:20.184
This book has several such passages. It is ɹrst of

7
00:00:20.184 --> 00:00:23.664
all a book about survival. Like so many German and

8
00:00:23.664 --> 00:00:27.144
East European Jews who thought themselves secure in the 1930s,

9
00:00:27.144 --> 00:00:30.624
Frankl was cast into the Nazi network of concentration and

10
00:00:30.624 --> 00:00:34.104
extermination camps. Miraculously, he survived, in the biblical phrase "a

11
00:00:34.104 --> 00:00:37.584
brand plucked from the ɹre." But his account in this

12
00:00:37.584 --> 00:00:41.064
book is less about his travails, what he suʃered and

13
00:00:41.064 --> 00:00:44.544
lost, than it is about the sources of his strength

14
00:00:44.544 --> 00:00:48.024
to survive. Several times in the course of the book,

15
00:00:48.024 --> 00:00:51.504
Frankl approvingly quotes the words of Nietzsche: "He who has

16
00:00:51.504 --> 00:00:54.984
a Why to live for can bear almost any How."

17
00:00:54.984 --> 00:00:58.464
He describes poignantly those prisoners who gave up on life,

18
00:00:58.464 --> 00:01:01.944
who had lost all hope for a future and were

19
00:01:01.944 --> 00:01:05.424
inevitably the ɹrst to die. They died less from lack

20
00:01:05.424 --> 00:01:08.904
of food or medicine than from lack of hope, lack

21
00:01:08.904 --> 00:01:12.384
of something to live for. By contrast, Frankl kept himself

22
00:01:12.384 --> 00:01:15.864
alive and kept hope alive by summoning up thoughts of

23
00:01:15.864 --> 00:01:19.344
his wife and the prospect of seeing her again, and

24
00:01:19.344 --> 00:01:22.824
by dreaming at one point of lecturing after the war

25
00:01:22.824 --> 00:01:26.304
about the psychological lessons to be learned from the Auschwitz

26
00:01:26.304 --> 00:01:29.784
experience. Clearly, many prisoners who desperately wanted to live did

27
00:01:29.784 --> 00:01:32.568
die, some from disease, some in the crematoria.

28
00:01:32.568 --> 00:01:36.048
But Frankl's concern is less with the question of why

29
00:01:36.048 --> 00:01:39.528
most died than it is with the question of why

30
00:01:39.528 --> 00:01:43.008
anyone at all survived. Terrible as it was, his experience

31
00:01:43.008 --> 00:01:46.488
in Auschwitz reinforced what was already one of his key

32
00:01:46.488 --> 00:01:49.968
ideas: Life is not primarily a quest for pleasure, as

33
00:01:49.968 --> 00:01:53.448
Freud believed, or a quest for power, as Alfred Adler

34
00:01:53.448 --> 00:01:56.928
taught, but a quest for meaning. The greatest task for

35
00:01:56.928 --> 00:02:00.408
any person is to ɹnd meaning in his or her

36
00:02:00.408 --> 00:02:03.192
life. Frankl saw three possible sources for meaning:

37
00:02:03.192 --> 00:02:06.672
in work (doing something signiɹcant), in love (caring for another

38
00:02:06.672 --> 00:02:10.152
person), and in courage during diʃcult times. Suʃering in and

39
00:02:10.152 --> 00:02:13.632
of itself is meaningless; we give our suʃering meaning by

40
00:02:13.632 --> 00:02:16.416
the way in which we respond to it.

41
00:02:16.584 --> 00:02:20.004
At one point, Frankl writes that a person "may remain

42
00:02:20.004 --> 00:02:23.424
brave, digniɹed and unselɹsh, or in the bitter ɹght for

43
00:02:23.424 --> 00:02:26.844
self-preservation he may forget his human dignity and become no

44
00:02:26.844 --> 00:02:30.264
more than an animal." He concedes that only a few

45
00:02:30.264 --> 00:02:33.684
prisoners of the Nazis were able to do the former,

46
00:02:33.684 --> 00:02:37.104
"but even one such example is suʃcient proof that man's

47
00:02:37.104 --> 00:02:40.524
inner strength may raise him above his outward fate." Finally,

48
00:02:40.524 --> 00:02:43.944
Frankl's most enduring insight, one that I have called on

49
00:02:43.944 --> 00:02:47.364
often in my own life and in countless counseling situations:

50
00:02:47.364 --> 00:02:50.784
Forces beyond your control can take away everything you possess

51
00:02:50.784 --> 00:02:54.204
except one thing, your freedom to choose how you will

52
00:02:54.204 --> 00:02:57.624
respond to the situation. You cannot control what happens to

53
00:02:57.624 --> 00:03:01.044
you in life, but you can always control what you

54
00:03:01.044 --> 00:03:04.122
will feel and do about what happens to you.

55
00:03:04.122 --> 00:03:07.542
There is a scene in Arthur Miller's play Incident at

56
00:03:07.542 --> 00:03:10.962
Vichy in which an upper-middle-class professional man appears before the

57
00:03:10.962 --> 00:03:14.382
Nazi authority that has occupied his town and shows his

58
00:03:14.382 --> 00:03:17.802
credentials: his university degrees, his letters of reference from prominent

59
00:03:17.802 --> 00:03:21.222
citizens, and so on. The Nazi asks him, "Is that

60
00:03:21.222 --> 00:03:24.642
everything you have?" The man nods. The Nazi throws it

61
00:03:24.642 --> 00:03:28.062
all in the wastebasket and tells him: "Good, now you

62
00:03:28.062 --> 00:03:31.482
have nothing." The man, whose self-esteem had always depended on

63
00:03:31.482 --> 00:03:34.902
the respect of others, is emotionally destroyed. Frankl would have

64
00:03:34.902 --> 00:03:38.322
argued that we are never left with nothing as long

65
00:03:38.322 --> 00:03:41.742
as we retain the freedom to choose how we will

66
00:03:41.742 --> 00:03:45.162
respond. My own congregational experience has shown me the truth

67
00:03:45.162 --> 00:03:48.582
of Frankl's insights. I have known successful businessmen who, upon

68
00:03:48.582 --> 00:03:52.002
retirement, lost all zest for life. Their work had given

69
00:03:52.002 --> 00:03:55.422
their lives meaning. Often it was the only thing that

70
00:03:55.422 --> 00:03:58.842
had given their lives meaning and, without it, they spent

71
00:03:58.842 --> 00:04:02.262
day after day sitting at home, depressed, "with nothing to

72
00:04:02.262 --> 00:04:05.682
do." I have known people who rose to the challenge

73
00:04:05.682 --> 00:04:09.102
of enduring the most terrible aʀictions and situations as long

74
00:04:09.102 --> 00:04:12.522
as they believed there was a point to their suʃering.

75
00:04:12.522 --> 00:04:15.942
Whether it was a family milestone they wanted to live

76
00:04:15.942 --> 00:04:19.362
long enough to share or the prospect of doctors ɹnding

77
00:04:19.362 --> 00:04:22.782
a cure by studying their illness, having a Why to

78
00:04:22.782 --> 00:04:25.518
live for enabled them to bear the How.

79
00:04:25.518 --> 00:04:28.596
And my own experience echoes Frankl's in another way.

80
00:04:28.596 --> 00:04:32.016
Just as the ideas in my book When Bad Things

81
00:04:32.016 --> 00:04:35.436
Happen to Good People gained power and credibility because they

82
00:04:35.436 --> 00:04:38.856
were oʃered in the context of my struggle to understand

83
00:04:38.856 --> 00:04:42.276
the illness and death of our son, Frankl's doctrine of

84
00:04:42.276 --> 00:04:45.696
logotherapy, curing the soul by leading it to find meaning

85
00:04:45.696 --> 00:04:49.116
in life, gains credibility against the background of his anguish

86
00:04:49.116 --> 00:04:52.536
in Auschwitz. The last half of the book without the

87
00:04:52.536 --> 00:04:55.956
ɹrst would be far less effective. I ɹnd it signiɹcant

88
00:04:55.956 --> 00:04:59.376
that the Foreword to the 1962 edition of Man's Search

89
00:04:59.376 --> 00:05:02.454
for Meaning was written by a prominent psychologist, Dr.

90
00:05:02.454 --> 00:05:05.874
Gordon Allport, and the Foreword to this new edition is

91
00:05:05.874 --> 00:05:09.360
written by a clergyman. We have come to recognize that

92
00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:12.840
this is a profoundly religious book. It insists that life

93
00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:16.320
is meaningful and that we must learn to see life

94
00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:19.800
as meaningful despite our circumstances. It emphasizes that there is

95
00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:23.280
an ultimate purpose to life. And in its original version,

96
00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:26.760
before a postscript was added, it concluded with one of

97
00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:29.892
the most religious sentences written in the twentieth century:

98
00:05:29.892 --> 00:05:33.372
We have come to know Man as he really is.

99
00:05:33.372 --> 00:05:36.852
After all, man is that being who invented the gas

100
00:05:36.852 --> 00:05:40.332
chambers of Auschwitz; however, he is also that being who

101
00:05:40.332 --> 00:05:43.812
entered those gas chambers upright, with the Lord's Prayer or

102
00:05:43.812 --> 00:05:46.596
the Shema Yisrael on his lips. HAROLD S.

103
00:05:46.596 --> 00:05:50.076
KUSHNER Harold S. Kushner is rabbi emeritus at Temple Israel

104
00:05:50.076 --> 00:05:53.556
in Natick, Massachusetts, and the author of several best-selling books,

105
00:05:53.556 --> 00:05:57.036
including When Bad Things Happen to Good People, Living a

106
00:05:57.036 --> 00:06:00.516
Life That Matters, and When All You've Ever Wanted Isn't

107
00:06:00.516 --> 00:06:03.996
Enough. PREFACE TO THE 1992 EDITION THIS BOOK HAS NOW

108
00:06:03.996 --> 00:06:07.476
LIVED TO SEE nearly one hundred printings in English-in addition

109
00:06:07.476 --> 00:06:10.260
to having been published in twenty-one other languages.

110
00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:13.740
And the English editions alone have sold more than three

111
00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:17.220
million copies. These are the dry facts, and they may

112
00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:20.700
well be the reason why reporters of American newspapers and

113
00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:24.180
particularly of American TV stations more often than not start

114
00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:26.964
their interviews, after listing these facts, by exclaiming:

115
00:06:26.964 --> 00:06:30.444
"Dr. Frankl, your book has become a true bestseller-how do

116
00:06:30.444 --> 00:06:33.924
you feel about such a success?" Whereupon I react by

117
00:06:33.924 --> 00:06:37.404
reporting that in the ɹrst place I do not at

118
00:06:37.404 --> 00:06:40.884
all see in the bestseller status of my book an

119
00:06:40.884 --> 00:06:44.364
achievement and accomplishment on my part but rather an expression

120
00:06:44.364 --> 00:06:47.844
of the misery of our time: if hundreds of thousands

121
00:06:47.844 --> 00:06:51.324
of people reach out for a book whose very title

122
00:06:51.324 --> 00:06:54.804
promises to deal with the question of a meaning to

123
00:06:54.804 --> 00:06:58.284
life, it must be a question that burns under their

124
00:06:58.284 --> 00:07:01.764
fingernails. To be sure, something else may have contributed to

125
00:07:01.764 --> 00:07:05.244
the impact of the book: its second, theoretical part ("Logother-

126
00:07:05.244 --> 00:07:08.724
apy in a Nutshell") boils down, as it were, to

127
00:07:08.724 --> 00:07:12.204
the lesson one may distill from the ɹrst part, the

128
00:07:12.204 --> 00:07:15.684
autobiographical account ("Experiences in a Concentration Camp"), whereas Part One

129
00:07:15.684 --> 00:07:18.468
serves as the existential validation of my theories.

130
00:07:18.468 --> 00:07:21.948
Thus, both parts mutually support their credibility. I had none

131
00:07:21.948 --> 00:07:25.428
of this in mind when I wrote the book in

132
00:07:25.428 --> 00:07:28.908
1945. And I did so within nine successive days and

133
00:07:28.908 --> 00:07:32.388
with the ɹrm determination that the book should be published

134
00:07:32.388 --> 00:07:35.868
anonymously. In fact, the ɹrst printing of the original German

135
00:07:35.868 --> 00:07:39.348
version does not show my name on the cover, though

136
00:07:39.348 --> 00:07:42.828
at the last moment, just before the book's initial publication,

137
00:07:42.828 --> 00:07:46.308
I did ɹnally give in to my friends who had

138
00:07:46.308 --> 00:07:49.788
urged me to let it be published with my name

139
00:07:49.788 --> 00:07:53.268
at least on the title page. At ɹrst, however, it

140
00:07:53.268 --> 00:07:56.748
had been written with the absolute conviction that, as an

141
00:07:56.748 --> 00:08:00.228
anonymous opus, it could never earn its author literary fame.

142
00:08:00.228 --> 00:08:03.608
I had wanted simply to convey to the reader by

143
00:08:03.608 --> 00:08:06.798
way of a concrete example that life holds a potential

144
00:08:06.798 --> 00:08:09.669
meaning under any conditions, even the most miserable ones.

145
00:08:09.669 --> 00:08:12.859
And I thought that if the point were demonstrated in

146
00:08:12.859 --> 00:08:16.049
a situation as extreme as that in a concentration camp,

147
00:08:16.049 --> 00:08:19.239
my book might gain a hearing. I therefore felt responsible

148
00:08:19.239 --> 00:08:22.429
for writing down what I had gone through, for I

149
00:08:22.429 --> 00:08:25.619
thought it might be helpful to people who are prone

150
00:08:25.619 --> 00:08:28.809
to despair. And so it is both strange and remarkable

151
00:08:28.809 --> 00:08:31.999
to me that-among some dozens of books I have authored-precisely

152
00:08:31.999 --> 00:08:35.189
this one, which I had intended to be published anonymously

153
00:08:35.189 --> 00:08:38.379
so that it could never build up any reputation on

154
00:08:38.379 --> 00:08:41.250
the part of the author, did become a success.

155
00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:44.440
Again and again I therefore admonish my students both in

156
00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:47.630
Europe and in America: "Don't aim at success-the more you

157
00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:50.820
aim at it and make it a target, the more

158
00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:54.010
you are going to miss it. For success, like happiness,

159
00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:57.200
cannot be pursued; it must ensue, and it only does

160
00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:00.390
so as the unintended side-eʃect of one's dedication to a

161
00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:03.580
cause greater than oneself or as the by-product of one's

162
00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:06.770
surrender to a person other than oneself. Happiness must happen,

163
00:09:06.770 --> 00:09:09.960
and the same holds for success: you have to let

164
00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:13.150
it happen by not caring about it. I want you

165
00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:16.340
to listen to what your conscience commands you to do

166
00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:19.530
and go on to carry it out to the best

167
00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:22.720
of your knowledge. Then you will live to see that

168
00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:25.910
in the long run-in the long run, I say!-success will

169
00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:29.100
follow you precisely because you had forgotten to think of

170
00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:32.290
it." The reader may ask me why I did not

171
00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:35.480
try to escape what was in store for me after

172
00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.670
Hitler had occupied Austria. Let me answer by recalling the

173
00:09:38.670 --> 00:09:41.860
following story. Shortly before the United States entered World War

174
00:09:41.860 --> 00:09:45.050
II, I received an invitation to come to the American

175
00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:47.921
Consulate in Vienna to pick up my immigration visa.

176
00:09:47.921 --> 00:09:51.111
My old parents were overjoyed because they expected that I

177
00:09:51.111 --> 00:09:54.301
would soon be allowed to leave Austria. I suddenly hesitated,

178
00:09:54.301 --> 00:09:57.491
however. The question beset me: could I really aʃord to

179
00:09:57.491 --> 00:10:00.681
leave my parents alone to face their fate, to be

180
00:10:00.681 --> 00:10:03.871
sent, sooner or later, to a concentration camp, or even

181
00:10:03.871 --> 00:10:07.061
to a socalled extermination camp? Where did my responsibility lie?

182
00:10:07.061 --> 00:10:10.251
Should I foster my brain child, logotherapy, by emigrating to

183
00:10:10.251 --> 00:10:12.803
fertile soil where I could write my books?

184
00:10:12.803 --> 00:10:15.993
Or should I concentrate on my duties as a real

185
00:10:15.993 --> 00:10:19.183
child, the child of my parents who had to do

186
00:10:19.183 --> 00:10:22.373
whatever he could to protect them? I pondered the problem

187
00:10:22.373 --> 00:10:25.563
this way and that but could not arrive at a

188
00:10:25.563 --> 00:10:28.753
solution; this was the type of dilemma that made one

189
00:10:28.753 --> 00:10:31.943
wish for "a hint from Heaven," as the phrase goes.

190
00:10:31.943 --> 00:10:35.133
It was then that I noticed a piece of marble

191
00:10:35.133 --> 00:10:38.488
lying on a table at home. When I asked my

192
00:10:38.488 --> 00:10:41.888
father about it, he explained that he had found it

193
00:10:41.888 --> 00:10:45.288
on the site where the National Socialists had burned down

194
00:10:45.288 --> 00:10:48.688
the largest Viennese synagogue. He had taken the piece home

195
00:10:48.688 --> 00:10:52.088
because it was a part of the tablets on which

196
00:10:52.088 --> 00:10:55.488
the Ten Commandments were inscribed. One gilded Hebrew letter was

197
00:10:55.488 --> 00:10:58.888
engraved on the piece; my father explained that this letter

198
00:10:58.888 --> 00:11:02.288
stood for one of the Commandments. Eagerly I asked, "Which

199
00:11:02.288 --> 00:11:05.688
one is it?" He answered, "Honor thy father and thy

200
00:11:05.688 --> 00:11:09.088
mother that thy days may be long upon the land."

201
00:11:09.088 --> 00:11:12.488
At that moment I decided to stay with my father

202
00:11:12.488 --> 00:11:15.888
and my mother upon the land, and to let the

203
00:11:15.888 --> 00:11:19.288
American visa lapse. VIKTOR E. FRANKL Vienna, 1992 I EXPERIENCES

204
00:11:19.288 --> 00:11:22.688
IN A CONCENTRATION CAMP THIS BOOK DOES NOT CLAIM TO

205
00:11:22.688 --> 00:11:26.088
BE an account of facts and events but of personal

206
00:11:26.088 --> 00:11:29.488
experiences, experiences which millions of prisoners have suʃered time and

207
00:11:29.488 --> 00:11:32.888
again. It is the inside story of a concentration camp,

208
00:11:32.888 --> 00:11:36.288
told by one of its survivors. This tale is not

209
00:11:36.288 --> 00:11:39.688
concerned with the great horrors, which have already been described

210
00:11:39.688 --> 00:11:43.088
often enough (though less often believed), but with the multitude

211
00:11:43.088 --> 00:11:46.488
of small torments. In other words, it will try to

212
00:11:46.488 --> 00:11:49.888
answer this question: How was everyday life in a concentration

213
00:11:49.888 --> 00:11:52.948
camp reɻected in the mind of the average prisoner?

214
00:11:52.948 --> 00:11:56.348
Most of the events described here did not take place

215
00:11:56.348 --> 00:11:59.748
in the large and famous camps, but in the small

216
00:11:59.748 --> 00:12:02.808
ones where most of the real extermination took place.

217
00:12:02.808 --> 00:12:06.208
This story is not about the suʃering and death of

218
00:12:06.208 --> 00:12:09.608
great heroes and martyrs, nor is it about the prominent

219
00:12:09.608 --> 00:12:13.008
Capos-prisoners who acted as trustees, having special privilegesor well-known prisoners.

220
00:12:13.008 --> 00:12:16.408
Thus it is not so much concerned with the suʃerings

221
00:12:16.408 --> 00:12:19.808
of the mighty, but with the sacriɹces, the cruciɹxion and

222
00:12:19.808 --> 00:12:23.208
the deaths of the great army of unknown and unrecorded

223
00:12:23.208 --> 00:12:26.608
victims. It was these common prisoners, who bore no distinguishing

224
00:12:26.608 --> 00:12:29.668
marks on their sleeves, whom the Capos really despised.

225
00:12:29.668 --> 00:12:33.068
While these ordinary prisoners had little or nothing to eat,

226
00:12:33.068 --> 00:12:36.468
the Capos were never hungry; in fact many of the

227
00:12:36.468 --> 00:12:39.868
Capos fared better in the camp than they had in

228
00:12:39.868 --> 00:12:43.268
their entire lives. Often they were harder on the prisoners

229
00:12:43.268 --> 00:12:46.668
than were the guards, and beat them more cruelly than

230
00:12:46.668 --> 00:12:50.068
the SS men did. These Capos, of course, were chosen

231
00:12:50.068 --> 00:12:53.468
only from those prisoners whose characters promised to make them

232
00:12:53.468 --> 00:12:56.868
suitable for such procedures, and if they did not comply

233
00:12:56.868 --> 00:13:00.268
with what was expected of them, they were immediately demoted.

234
00:13:00.268 --> 00:13:03.668
They soon became much like the SS men and the

235
00:13:03.668 --> 00:13:07.068
camp wardens and may be judged on a similar psychological

236
00:13:07.068 --> 00:13:10.468
basis. It is easy for the outsider to get the

237
00:13:10.468 --> 00:13:13.868
wrong conception of camp life, a conception mingled with sentiment

238
00:13:13.868 --> 00:13:17.268
and pity. Little does he know of the hard ɹght

239
00:13:17.268 --> 00:13:20.883
for existence which raged among the prisoners. This was an

240
00:13:20.883 --> 00:13:24.253
unrelenting struggle for daily bread and for life itself, for

241
00:13:24.253 --> 00:13:27.623
one's own sake or for that of a good friend.

242
00:13:27.623 --> 00:13:30.993
Let us take the case of a transport which was

243
00:13:30.993 --> 00:13:34.363
oʃcially announced to transfer a certain number of prisoners to

244
00:13:34.363 --> 00:13:37.733
another camp; but it was a fairly safe guess that

245
00:13:37.733 --> 00:13:40.429
its ɹnal destination would be the gas chambers.

246
00:13:40.429 --> 00:13:43.799
A selection of sick or feeble prisoners incapable of work

247
00:13:43.799 --> 00:13:47.169
would be sent to one of the big central camps

248
00:13:47.169 --> 00:13:49.865
which were ɹtted with gas chambers and crematoriums.

249
00:13:49.865 --> 00:13:53.235
The selection process was the signal for a free ɹght

250
00:13:53.235 --> 00:13:56.268
among all the prisoners, or of group against group.

251
00:13:56.268 --> 00:13:59.638
All that mattered was that one's own name and that

252
00:13:59.638 --> 00:14:03.008
of one's friend were crossed oʃ the list of victims,

253
00:14:03.008 --> 00:14:06.378
though everyone knew that for each man saved another victim

254
00:14:06.378 --> 00:14:09.748
had to be found. A deɹnite number of prisoners had

255
00:14:09.748 --> 00:14:13.118
to go with each transport. It did not really matter

256
00:14:13.118 --> 00:14:16.488
which, since each of them was nothing but a number.

257
00:14:16.488 --> 00:14:19.858
On their admission to the camp (at least this was

258
00:14:19.858 --> 00:14:23.228
the method in Auschwitz) all their documents had been taken

259
00:14:23.228 --> 00:14:26.598
from them, together with their other possessions. Each prisoner, therefore,

260
00:14:26.598 --> 00:14:29.968
had had an opportunity to claim a ɹctitious name or

261
00:14:29.968 --> 00:14:32.664
profession; and for various reasons many did this.

262
00:14:32.664 --> 00:14:35.697
The authorities were interested only in the captives' numbers.

263
00:14:35.697 --> 00:14:39.067
These numbers were often tattooed on their skin, and also

264
00:14:39.067 --> 00:14:42.437
had to be sewn to a certain spot on the

265
00:14:42.437 --> 00:14:45.807
trousers, jacket, or coat. Any guard who wanted to make

266
00:14:45.807 --> 00:14:49.177
a charge against a prisoner just glanced at his number

267
00:14:49.177 --> 00:14:52.547
(and how we dreaded such glances!); he never asked for

268
00:14:52.547 --> 00:14:55.917
his name. To return to the convoy about to depart.

269
00:14:55.917 --> 00:14:59.287
There was neither time nor desire to consider moral or

270
00:14:59.287 --> 00:15:02.657
ethical issues. Every man was controlled by one thought only:

271
00:15:02.657 --> 00:15:06.027
to keep himself alive for the family waiting for him

272
00:15:06.027 --> 00:15:09.397
at home, and to save his friends. With no hesitation,

273
00:15:09.397 --> 00:15:12.767
therefore, he would arrange for another prisoner, another "number," to

274
00:15:12.767 --> 00:15:16.137
take his place in the transport. As I have already

275
00:15:16.137 --> 00:15:19.507
mentioned, the process of selecting Capos was a negative one;

276
00:15:19.507 --> 00:15:22.877
only the most brutal of the prisoners were chosen for

277
00:15:22.877 --> 00:15:25.573
this job (although there were some happy exceptions).

278
00:15:25.573 --> 00:15:28.943
But apart from the selection of Capos which was undertaken

279
00:15:28.943 --> 00:15:32.313
by the SS, there was a sort of self-selecting process

280
00:15:32.313 --> 00:15:35.683
going on the whole time among all of the prisoners.

281
00:15:35.683 --> 00:15:39.053
On the average, only those prisoners could keep alive who,

282
00:15:39.053 --> 00:15:42.423
after years of trekking from camp to camp, had lost

283
00:15:42.423 --> 00:15:45.793
all scruples in their ɹght for existence; they were prepared

284
00:15:45.793 --> 00:15:49.163
to use every means, honest and otherwise, even brutal force,

285
00:15:49.163 --> 00:15:52.533
theft, and betrayal of their friends, in order to save

286
00:15:52.533 --> 00:15:55.903
themselves. We who have come back, by the aid of

287
00:15:55.903 --> 00:15:59.273
many lucky chances or miracles-whatever one may choose to call

288
00:15:59.273 --> 00:16:02.306
them-we know: the best of us did not return.

289
00:16:02.306 --> 00:16:05.676
Many factual accounts about concentration camps are already on record.

290
00:16:05.736 --> 00:16:09.266
Here, facts will be signiɹcant only as far as they

291
00:16:09.266 --> 00:16:12.796
are part of a man's experiences. It is the exact

292
00:16:12.796 --> 00:16:16.326
nature of these experiences that the following essay will attempt

293
00:16:16.326 --> 00:16:19.856
to describe. For those who have been inmates in a

294
00:16:19.856 --> 00:16:23.386
camp, it will attempt to explain their experiences in the

295
00:16:23.386 --> 00:16:26.916
light of present-day knowledge. And for those who have never

296
00:16:26.916 --> 00:16:30.446
been inside, it may help them to comprehend, and above

297
00:16:30.446 --> 00:16:33.976
all to understand, the experiences of that only too small

298
00:16:33.976 --> 00:16:37.506
percentage of prisoners who survived and who now ɹnd life

299
00:16:37.506 --> 00:16:41.036
very diʃcult. These former prisoners often say, "We dislike talking

300
00:16:41.036 --> 00:16:44.566
about our experiences. No explanations are needed for those who

301
00:16:44.566 --> 00:16:48.096
have been inside, and the others will understand neither how

302
00:16:48.096 --> 00:16:51.626
we felt then nor how we feel now." To attempt

303
00:16:51.626 --> 00:16:55.156
a methodical presentation of the subject is very diʃcult, as

304
00:16:55.156 --> 00:16:58.686
psychology requires a certain scientiɹc detachment. But does a man

305
00:16:58.686 --> 00:17:02.216
who makes his observations while he himself is a prisoner

306
00:17:02.216 --> 00:17:05.746
possess the necessary detachment? Such detachment is granted to the

307
00:17:05.746 --> 00:17:09.276
outsider, but he is too far removed to make any

308
00:17:09.276 --> 00:17:12.453
statements of real value. Only the man inside knows.

309
00:17:12.453 --> 00:17:15.983
His judgments may not be objective; his evaluations may be

310
00:17:15.983 --> 00:17:19.513
out of proportion. This is inevitable. An attempt must be

311
00:17:19.513 --> 00:17:23.043
made to avoid any personal bias, and that is the

312
00:17:23.043 --> 00:17:25.867
real diʃculty of a book of this kind.

313
00:17:25.867 --> 00:17:29.397
At times it will be necessary to have the courage

314
00:17:29.397 --> 00:17:32.927
to tell of very intimate experiences. I had intended to

315
00:17:32.927 --> 00:17:36.104
write this book anonymously, using my prison number only.

316
00:17:36.104 --> 00:17:39.634
But when the manuscript was completed, I saw that as

317
00:17:39.634 --> 00:17:43.164
an anonymous publication it would lose half its value, and

318
00:17:43.164 --> 00:17:46.694
that I must have the courage to state my convictions

319
00:17:46.694 --> 00:17:50.224
openly. I therefore refrained from deleting any of the passages,

320
00:17:50.224 --> 00:17:53.048
in spite of an intense dislike of exhibitionism.

321
00:17:53.048 --> 00:17:56.578
I shall leave it to others to distill the contents

322
00:17:56.578 --> 00:18:00.108
of this book into dry theories. These might become a

323
00:18:00.108 --> 00:18:03.638
contribution to the psychology of prison life, which was investigated

324
00:18:03.638 --> 00:18:07.168
after the First World War, and which acquainted us with

325
00:18:07.168 --> 00:18:10.698
the syndrome of "barbed wire sickness." We are indebted to

326
00:18:10.698 --> 00:18:14.228
the Second World War for enriching our knowledge of the

327
00:18:14.228 --> 00:18:17.758
"psychopathology of the masses" (if I may quote a variation

328
00:18:17.758 --> 00:18:21.288
of the well-known phrase and title of a book by

329
00:18:21.288 --> 00:18:24.818
LeBon), for the war gave us the war of nerves

330
00:18:24.818 --> 00:18:28.348
and it gave us the concentration camp. As this story

331
00:18:28.348 --> 00:18:31.878
is about my experiences as an ordinary prisoner, it is

332
00:18:31.878 --> 00:18:35.408
important that I mention, not without pride, that I was

333
00:18:35.408 --> 00:18:38.938
not employed as a psychiatrist in camp, or even as

334
00:18:38.938 --> 00:18:41.762
a doctor, except for the last few weeks.

335
00:18:41.762 --> 00:18:45.292
A few of my colleagues were lucky enough to be

336
00:18:45.292 --> 00:18:48.822
employed in poorly heated ɹrst-aid posts applying bandages made of

337
00:18:48.822 --> 00:18:52.352
scraps of waste paper. But I was Number 119,104, and

338
00:18:52.352 --> 00:18:55.882
most of the time I was digging and laying tracks

339
00:18:55.882 --> 00:18:59.650
for railway lines. At one time, my job was to

340
00:18:59.650 --> 00:19:03.230
dig a tunnel, without help, for a water main under

341
00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:06.094
a road. This feat did not go unrewarded;

342
00:19:06.094 --> 00:19:09.674
just before Christmas 1944, I was presented with a gift

343
00:19:09.674 --> 00:19:13.254
of so-called "premium coupons." These were issued by the construction

344
00:19:13.254 --> 00:19:16.476
ɹrm to which we were practically sold as slaves:

345
00:19:16.476 --> 00:19:20.056
the ɹrm paid the camp authorities a ɹxed price per

346
00:19:20.056 --> 00:19:23.636
day, per prisoner. The coupons cost the ɹrm ɹfty pfennigs

347
00:19:23.636 --> 00:19:27.216
each and could be exchanged for six cigarettes, often weeks

348
00:19:27.216 --> 00:19:30.796
later, although they sometimes lost their validity. I became the

349
00:19:30.796 --> 00:19:33.660
proud owner of a token worth twelve cigarettes.

350
00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:37.240
But more important, the cigarettes could be exchanged for twelve

351
00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:40.820
soups, and twelve soups were often a very real respite

352
00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:44.400
from starvation. The privilege of actually smoking cigarettes was reserved

353
00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:47.980
for the Capo, who had his assured quota of weekly

354
00:19:47.980 --> 00:19:51.560
coupons; or possibly for a prisoner who worked as a

355
00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:55.140
foreman in a warehouse or workshop and received a few

356
00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:58.720
cigarettes in exchange for doing dangerous jobs. The only exceptions

357
00:19:58.720 --> 00:20:02.300
to this were those who had lost the will to

358
00:20:02.300 --> 00:20:05.164
live and wanted to "enjoy" their last days.

359
00:20:05.164 --> 00:20:08.744
Thus, when we saw a comrade smoking his own cigarettes,

360
00:20:08.744 --> 00:20:12.324
we knew he had given up faith in his strength

361
00:20:12.324 --> 00:20:15.904
to carry on, and, once lost, the will to live

362
00:20:15.904 --> 00:20:19.484
seldom returned. When one examines the vast amount of material

363
00:20:19.484 --> 00:20:23.064
which has been amassed as the result of many prisoners'

364
00:20:23.064 --> 00:20:26.644
observations and experiences, three phases of the inmate's mental reactions

365
00:20:26.644 --> 00:20:30.224
to camp life become apparent: the period following his admission;

366
00:20:30.224 --> 00:20:33.804
the period when he is well entrenched in camp routine;

367
00:20:33.804 --> 00:20:36.668
and the period following his release and liberation.

368
00:20:36.668 --> 00:20:39.890
The symptom that characterizes the ɹrst phase is shock.

369
00:20:39.890 --> 00:20:43.470
Under certain conditions shock may even precede the prisoner's formal

370
00:20:43.470 --> 00:20:47.050
admission to the camp. I shall give as an example

371
00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:50.630
the circumstances of my own admission. Fifteen hundred persons had

372
00:20:50.630 --> 00:20:53.852
been traveling by train for several days and nights:

373
00:20:53.852 --> 00:20:57.432
there were eighty people in each coach. All had to

374
00:20:57.432 --> 00:21:01.012
lie on top of their luggage, the few remnants of

375
00:21:01.012 --> 00:21:04.592
their personal possessions. The carriages were so full that only

376
00:21:04.592 --> 00:21:08.172
the top parts of the windows were free to let

377
00:21:08.172 --> 00:21:11.752
in the grey of dawn. Everyone expected the train to

378
00:21:11.752 --> 00:21:15.332
head for some munitions factory, in which we would be

379
00:21:15.332 --> 00:21:18.912
employed as forced labor. We did not know whether we

380
00:21:18.912 --> 00:21:21.776
were still in Silesia or already in Poland.

381
00:21:21.776 --> 00:21:25.356
The engine's whistle had an uncanny sound, like a cry

382
00:21:25.356 --> 00:21:28.936
for help sent out in commiseration for the unhappy load

383
00:21:28.936 --> 00:21:31.800
which it was destined to lead into perdition.

384
00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:35.022
Then the train shunted, obviously nearing a main station.

385
00:21:35.022 --> 00:21:38.602
Suddenly a cry broke from the ranks of the anxious

386
00:21:38.602 --> 00:21:42.182
passengers, "There is a sign, Auschwitz!" Everyone's heart missed a

387
00:21:42.182 --> 00:21:45.762
beat at that moment. Auschwitz-the very name stood for all

388
00:21:45.762 --> 00:21:49.563
that was horrible: gas chambers, crematoriums, massacres. Slowly, almost hesitatingly,

389
00:21:49.563 --> 00:21:53.093
the train moved on as if it wanted to spare

390
00:21:53.093 --> 00:21:56.270
its passengers the dreadful realization as long as possible:

391
00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:59.800
Auschwitz! With the progressive dawn, the outlines of an immense

392
00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:03.330
camp became visible: long stretches of several rows of barbed

393
00:22:03.330 --> 00:22:06.860
wire fences; watch towers; searchlights; and long columns of ragged

394
00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:10.390
human ɹgures, grey in the greyness of dawn, trekking along

395
00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:13.920
the straight desolate roads, to what destination we did not

396
00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:17.097
know. There were isolated shouts and whistles of command.

397
00:22:17.097 --> 00:22:20.627
We did not know their meaning. My imagination led me

398
00:22:20.627 --> 00:22:23.451
to see gallows with people dangling on them.

399
00:22:23.451 --> 00:22:26.981
I was horriɹed, but this was just as well, because

400
00:22:26.981 --> 00:22:30.511
step by step we had to become accustomed to a

401
00:22:30.511 --> 00:22:34.041
terrible and immense horror. Eventually we moved into the station.

402
00:22:34.041 --> 00:22:36.865
The initial silence was interrupted by shouted commands.

403
00:22:36.865 --> 00:22:40.395
We were to hear those rough, shrill tones from then

404
00:22:40.395 --> 00:22:43.572
on, over and over again in all the camps.

405
00:22:43.572 --> 00:22:47.102
Their sound was almost like the last cry of a

406
00:22:47.102 --> 00:22:50.632
victim, and yet there was a diʃerence. It had a

407
00:22:50.632 --> 00:22:54.162
rasping hoarseness, as if it came from the throat of

408
00:22:54.162 --> 00:22:57.692
a man who had to keep shouting like that, a

409
00:22:57.692 --> 00:23:00.516
man who was being murdered again and again.

410
00:23:00.516 --> 00:23:04.046
The carriage doors were ɻung open and a small detachment

411
00:23:04.046 --> 00:23:07.576
of prisoners stormed inside. They wore striped uniforms, their heads

412
00:23:07.576 --> 00:23:11.106
were shaved, but they looked well fed. They spoke in

413
00:23:11.106 --> 00:23:14.636
every possible European tongue, and all with a certain amount

414
00:23:14.636 --> 00:23:17.460
of humor, which sounded grotesque under the circumstances.

415
00:23:17.460 --> 00:23:20.990
Like a drowning man clutching a straw, my inborn optimism

416
00:23:20.990 --> 00:23:24.520
(which has often controlled my feelings even in the most

417
00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:28.050
desperate situations) clung to this thought: These prisoners look quite

418
00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:31.580
well, they seem to be in good spirits and even

419
00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:35.110
laugh. Who knows? I might manage to share their favorable

420
00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:38.640
position. In psychiatry there is a certain condition known as

421
00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:42.170
"delusion of reprieve." The condemned man, immediately before his execution,

422
00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:45.700
gets the illusion that he might be reprieved at the

423
00:23:45.700 --> 00:23:49.230
very last minute. We, too, clung to shreds of hope

424
00:23:49.230 --> 00:23:52.760
and believed to the last moment that it would not

425
00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:56.290
be so bad. Just the sight of the red cheeks

426
00:23:56.290 --> 00:23:59.820
and round faces of those prisoners was a great encouragement.

427
00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:03.350
Little did we know then that they formed a specially

428
00:24:03.350 --> 00:24:06.880
chosen elite, who for years had been the receiving squad

429
00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:10.410
for new transports as they rolled into the station day

430
00:24:10.410 --> 00:24:13.940
after day. They took charge of the new arrivals and

431
00:24:13.940 --> 00:24:16.764
their luggage, including scarce items and smuggled jewelry.

432
00:24:16.764 --> 00:24:20.294
Auschwitz must have been a strange spot in this Europe

433
00:24:20.294 --> 00:24:23.824
of the last years of the war. There must have

434
00:24:23.824 --> 00:24:27.354
been unique treasures of gold and silver, platinum and diamonds,

435
00:24:27.354 --> 00:24:30.884
not only in the huge storehouses but also in the

436
00:24:30.884 --> 00:24:34.414
hands of the SS. Fifteen hundred captives were cooped up

437
00:24:34.414 --> 00:24:37.944
in a shed built to accommodate probably two hundred at

438
00:24:37.944 --> 00:24:41.224
the most. We were cold and hungry and there was

439
00:24:41.224 --> 00:24:44.424
not enough room for everyone to squat on the bare

440
00:24:44.424 --> 00:24:47.624
ground, let alone to lie down. One ɹve-ounce piece of

441
00:24:47.624 --> 00:24:50.184
bread was our only food in four days.

442
00:24:50.184 --> 00:24:53.384
Yet I heard the senior prisoners in charge of the

443
00:24:53.384 --> 00:24:56.584
shed bargain with one member of the receiving party about

444
00:24:56.584 --> 00:24:59.784
a tie-pin made of platinum and diamonds. Most of the

445
00:24:59.784 --> 00:25:02.984
proɹts would eventually be traded for liquor-schnapps. I do not

446
00:25:02.984 --> 00:25:06.184
remember any more just how many thousands of marks were

447
00:25:06.184 --> 00:25:09.384
needed to purchase the quantity of schnapps required for a

448
00:25:09.384 --> 00:25:12.584
"gay evening," but I do know that those long-term prisoners

449
00:25:12.584 --> 00:25:15.784
needed schnapps. Under such conditions, who could blame them for

450
00:25:15.784 --> 00:25:18.984
trying to dope themselves? There was another group of prisoners

451
00:25:18.984 --> 00:25:22.184
who got liquor supplied in almost unlimited quantities by the

452
00:25:22.184 --> 00:25:25.384
SS: these were the men who were employed in the

453
00:25:25.384 --> 00:25:28.584
gas chambers and crematoriums, and who knew very well that

454
00:25:28.584 --> 00:25:31.784
one day they would be relieved by a new shift

455
00:25:31.784 --> 00:25:34.984
of men, and that they would have to leave their

456
00:25:34.984 --> 00:25:37.544
enforced role of executioner and become victims themselves.

457
00:25:37.544 --> 00:25:40.744
Nearly everyone in our transport lived under the illusion that

458
00:25:40.744 --> 00:25:43.944
he would be reprieved, that everything would yet be well.

459
00:25:43.944 --> 00:25:47.144
We did not realize the meaning behind the scene that

460
00:25:47.144 --> 00:25:50.344
was to follow presently. We were told to leave our

461
00:25:50.344 --> 00:25:53.544
luggage in the train and to fall into two lines-women

462
00:25:53.544 --> 00:25:56.744
on one side, men on the other-in order to ɹle

463
00:25:56.744 --> 00:25:59.944
past a senior SS oʃcer. Surprisingly enough, I had the

464
00:25:59.944 --> 00:26:02.504
courage to hide my haversack under my coat.

465
00:26:02.504 --> 00:26:05.384
My line ɹled past the oʃcer, man by man.

466
00:26:05.384 --> 00:26:08.584
I realized that it would be dangerous if the oʃcer

467
00:26:08.584 --> 00:26:11.784
spotted my bag. He would at least knock me down;

468
00:26:11.784 --> 00:26:14.984
I knew that from previous experience. Instinctively, I straightened on

469
00:26:14.984 --> 00:26:18.184
approaching the oʃcer, so that he would not notice my

470
00:26:18.184 --> 00:26:21.384
heavy load. Then I was face to face with him.

471
00:26:21.384 --> 00:26:24.584
